{"actual_usd":0.158815,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":202,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"Yeah, that's the snag everybody hits.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light's catching on the well chain.* \"Christians aren't saying three separate beings who happen to all be divine, like three gods sharing a category. We're saying one God in being, three in person — the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God, and they are not each other.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once, thinking how easy this is to say too fast and make it worse.* \"If that sounds weird, it's because it is. Monotheism holds because God's 'what' is one, not three. The threeness is in the personal distinction, not in three separate divine essences. So not three gods standing side by side — one God, eternally Father, Son, and Spirit.\"\n\n\"Want the short church-history version, or the plain-English version with the usual bad analogies crossed out?\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.844230000000014,"run_id":"1cced950-6a38-4e0f-a21c-d56e64722cfc"}
